3. Notices and Clarifications

3.1 Scope of License
These notices are informational only and do not alter, supersede, or add restrictions to the MIT License above. If a conflict appears to exist, the MIT License text controls.

3.2 High-Risk Activity and Safety Guidance
This software is not designed or certified for use in hazardous environments or high-risk activities (including, without limitation, life-support systems, emergency dispatch, aircraft navigation or communication systems, air traffic control, nuclear facilities, medical devices, or weapons systems). If you choose to deploy the software in contexts where failure could result in injury, death, or severe environmental or property damage, you are solely responsible for implementing appropriate risk assessments, redundancies, supervision, and safety certifications.

3.3 Robotics-Specific Safety Expectations
The software includes a domain-specific language and tooling that can be used to orchestrate automation and robotics tasks through separate hardware or service modules. The software itself does not control hardware directly and does not provide safety guarantees. You are responsible for validating task logic, guarding dangerous motions, enforcing stop conditions, and complying with applicable safety standards (for example, ISO 10218, ISO/TS 15066, IEC 61508, or regional equivalents). Always test tasks in simulation or restricted modes before live operation. Provide physical e-stop mechanisms and administrative controls when deploying on real systems.

3.4 Third-Party Components and Sub-licenses
This project may include or depend upon third-party packages, tools, or assets. Each third-party component remains subject to its own license. Nothing in this document purports to grant rights to third-party code or trademarks. See the repository’s dependency metadata and the respective upstream license files for details.

